{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"bf8779fd-b0bd-4f7c-a32b-2a4faee2feb0","content":"There's no repository-specific documentation on this topic, so here's the general guidance:\n\n**Recovering a crash dump on macOS without `createdump`:**\n\n1. **Enable macOS core dumps:**\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n\n2. **Set the core dump directory** (macOS defaults to `/cores/`):\n   ```bash\n   sudo sysctl kern.corefile=/cores/core.%P\n   ```\n\n3. **Reproduce the crash.** The OS writes a Mach-O core file to `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\n4. **If System Integrity Protection (SIP) blocks core dumps**, you may need to temporarily disable it (boot to Recovery Mode → `csrutil disable`), though this is rarely needed for your own apps.\n\n5. **Analyze the dump** with `lldb`:\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.12345 /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n\n6. **Alternatively**, macOS automatically captures crash reports in:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   These `.ips` / `.crash` files contain stack traces and can be a quick substitute for a full core dump.\n\n**Key note for NativeAOT:** Since there's no managed runtime, `lldb` works directly with native symbols. If you published with debug symbols (`-p:StripSymbols=false`), you'll get full stack traces.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e8702134-fbf9-48e3-8391-f9259c1afeca","outputTokens":343,"requestId":"DA0E:CA3A1:229C3C3:2657E1B:6A03D8E3"},"id":"ea1a7774-c1f6-4d69-b597-292a901ba9b8","timestamp":"2026-05-13T01:50:36.858Z","parentId":"08e157b5-6e6e-456a-a2de-1c350cfbbfd2"}
